<subSubSection id="ACD739289CB906335B3D2AAED08E837A" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="0219F65E27A6E3DDA9772413B1306EEA" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="110B7158021B5F8BA2E108466DE7152C" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
As noted above in the description of 
<taxonomicName id="C413A00E8334CB2ECDCCE3A931075E8E" class="Arachnida" family="Euctenizidae" genus="Aptostichus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aptostichus nateevansi" order="Araneae" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nateevansi">Aptostichus nateevansi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="3832EC2CECDEEF0867F1F5B34D16D627" class="Arachnida" family="Euctenizidae" genus="Aptostichus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aptostichus chiricahua" order="Araneae" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chiricahua">Aptostichus chiricahua</taxonomicName>
has a mating clasper that is very similar to the California Channel Island species and thus may be closely related despite the disjunct distribution.
</paragraph>
